## How to read this chapter

This final chapter presents Sakhalin Ainu (Enchiw) <strong>as connected text</strong>. The
preceding chapters isolated single constructions; here those constructions are
seen working together in their natural habitat — the narrative line, the
quoted speech, the chained clause closed by a reportative. Each text is given
in the four-line interlinear format used throughout the grammar (surface form
where it differs, morpheme segmentation, aligned gloss, free translation),
with its source, dialect tag, and philological notes attached to each line.

The selection spans the island. The richest fully glossed running text happens
to be an east-coast folktale — Piłsudski's flatfish tale, re-edited by <Cite key="Sakaguchi 2020" paren={false} /> — and that text anchors the chapter.
It is paired with two west-coast tales, the West-central Dobrotvorskij
dialogues, and modern west-coast revival prose, so that the two coasts can be
read side by side. Every form here is attested in its cited edition; where a
segmentation is the editor's reconstruction or my own, the notes say so.

A word on the <strong>oral genres</strong> these texts belong to. Sakhalin oral literature
distinguishes several named kinds: <W w="tuytah" gloss="folktale" /> (the prose
fairy tale, often with inserted songs, told in the third person or with the
narrator-shifting technique discussed below); <W w="ucaskoma" gloss="legend" />
(legend, traditional knowledge); <W w="oyna" gloss="kamuy narrative" />
(the deity-narrative); and <W w="hawki" gloss="epic" /> (heroic epic). The
west-coast southwest has in addition a genre of *carahaw*, "rumour tales" <Cite key="Chiri 1942" />. The closing formula <W w="hemaka" gloss="the end" />
and the pervasive line-final reportative <W w="manu" gloss="it is said" /> are
the signature surface marks of the folktale register.

## Text 1 — East-coast *tuytah*: "The Flatfish-man and the Sculpin-man"

Our anchor text is Piłsudski's Tuita 3, recorded on the east coast and
re-edited with a full morpheme gloss by <Cite key="Sakaguchi 2020" paren={false} />.
It is a *tuytah* that opens in the third person, shifts into the flatfish-man's
own first-person voice partway through, and shifts back — the **person-shifting
narrative technique** characteristic of Piłsudski's 1903 east-coast tales, in
which the <Gl t="PRM" /> set (`-an`/`an=`/`i-`) cross-references the foregrounded
narrator. The tale also showcases the east-coast collective suffix <Gl t="COLL" /> `-ahci`, the belonging (<Gl t="POSS" />) form on relational
nouns, and the quotative frame `nah … yee`.

The opening line establishes the two protagonists and immediately uses the
collective, which agrees with the dual subject:

<Example
	ain="pon kapariw ohkayo poy sohkana ohkayo u-tur[a] okay-ahci"
	gloss="small flatfish man small sculpin man RECP-together.with live.PL-COLL"
	surface="Pon kapariw ohkayo poy sohkana ohkayo utur okay-ahci."
	free="A small flatfish-man and a small sculpin-man lived together."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="55 (Tuita 3, l. 1)"
	dialect="East" />

The flatfish-man announces his quest in direct speech, framed by the
quotative <Gl t="QUOT" /> `nah` followed by the verb of saying <W w="yee" gloss="say" />.
Inside the quote, purpose is carried by `kusu` and the allative goal by the
Sakhalin postposition <W w="onne" gloss="toward, into" />:

<Example
	ain="pon kapariw ohkayo rep-un mosiri onne mah-nuu kusu nah yee"
	gloss="small flatfish man sea-exist country toward wife-take in.order.to QUOT say"
	surface="Pon kapariw ohkayo &quot;Rep-un mosiri onne mah-nuu kusu.&quot; nah yee."
	free="The small flatfish-man said, ‘I will go to the offshore country to take a wife.’"
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="55 (Tuita 3, l. 2)"
	dialect="East" />

The bride is introduced with the belonging form <Gl t="POSS" /> on <W w="mahpoo" gloss="daughter" /> and the equative copula <Gl t="COP" /> `nee`
closed by the reportative <Gl t="REP" /> `manu`:

<Example
	ain="kakan mahpoo-ho teekoro pirika moromahpo nee manu"
	gloss="governor daughter-POSS very beautiful young.woman COP REP"
	free="Kakan's daughter was a very beautiful young woman, it is said."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="55 (Tuita 3, l. 4)"
	dialect="East"
	note="moromahpo is a literary tuytah word for ‘young woman’ (Chiri 1942)." />

The motive clause stacks two `kusu` "because" subordinators — one over a
nominalised clause ("because he heard that"), one over the desiderative <Gl t="DESID" /> `rusuy`:

<Example
	ain="nah(a) nuu-hu kusu sam rusuy kusu rep-un"
	gloss="QUOT hear-NMLZ because marry DESID because sea-go.to"
	free="Because he heard that, and because he wanted to marry her, he went out to the offshore country."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="55 (Tuita 3, l. 5)"
	dialect="East" />

At this point the narrative voice shifts: the flatfish-man becomes the
first-person narrator, and the <Gl t="PRM" /> S-suffix `-an` appears on the
plural stem <W w="ahup" gloss="enter (plural)" />. The dipper is referred to by
its belonging form `kahkum-ihi`:

<Example
	ain="kahkum-ihi onnay-ke ta ahup-an"
	gloss="dipper-POSS inside-place LOC enter.PL-PRM.S"
	free="I got inside the dipper."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="56 (Tuita 3, l. 7)"
	dialect="East"
	note="The shift into the flatfish-man's first-person self-narration; PRM S-suffix -an." />

A subordinate clause of cause stacks the reflexive <Gl t="REFL" /> `yay-` and
the applicative <Gl t="APPL" /> `ko-` on the light verb `-kara` "do",
illustrating the prefix-stacking that the valency chapter describes:

<Example
	ain="nea pon moromahpo teekor[o] ana[h] yay-ko-raanuh-kara kusu"
	gloss="that little young.woman very.much EMPH REFL-APPL-love-do because"
	free="because that young woman loved me very much,"
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="56 (Tuita 3, l. 9)"
	dialect="East" />

A reported question turns the loved-one's bewilderment into a content question,
with the second-person A-prefix `e-` and a nominalised verb closed by the
east-coast sentence-final interrogative `hetane-ana`:

<Example
	ain="hemata kusu ene an pon kapariw e-raanup-ihi hetane-ana"
	gloss="what for like.that exist.SG small flatfish 2.A-love-POSS Q"
	free="‘Why do you love such a small flatfish-man?’"
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="56 (Tuita 3, l. 12)"
	dialect="East" />

A rival suitor's arrival is staged with the prolative <Gl t="PROL" /> `peka`
"along, through" and the male-protagonist word <W w="horokewpo" gloss="young man" />:

<Example
	ain="tay sine-antoo ta soy peeka horokewpo itah haw an"
	gloss="this one-day LOC outside through man speak voice exist.SG"
	surface="tay sin[e]antoo ta soy peeka horokewpo itah haw an."
	free="One day, there was the voice of a man speaking outside the house."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="57 (Tuita 3, l. 15)"
	dialect="East" />

When two people act, both the verb of going and the verb of saying take the
collective <Gl t="COLL" /> — a clear demonstration that `-hci`/`-si` agrees with
participant number:

<Example
	ain="tura niina-hci kusu nah yee-si"
	gloss="together.with gather.firewood-COLL will QUOT say-COLL"
	free="‘Let's go gather firewood together,’ they said."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="57 (Tuita 3, l. 18)"
	dialect="East"
	note="Both niina-hci and yee-si carry the collective because two people act." />

The climactic line is Sakaguchi's chief evidence that the collective `-ahci`
can yield a <strong>passive</strong> reading: here `ocipa` "throw" carries `-hsi` although
the agent (the rival) is singular and definite, and the patient is the
flatfish-man:

<Example
	ain="pon kapariw ohkayo iso cara-(ha) onne ocipa-hsi"
	gloss="small flatfish man bear mouth-(POSS) toward throw-COLL"
	free="The small flatfish-man was thrown toward the bear's mouth."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="58 (Tuita 3, l. 21)"
	dialect="East"
	note="COLL on a singular definite agent — Sakaguchi's evidence for a passive use; whether COLL is genuinely a passive or an impersonal plural that yields a passive reading is left open." />

The bear dies and the flatfish-man descends, the singular motion stem <W w="san" gloss="come down (singular)" /> contrasting with its plural
counterpart `sap`:

<Example
	ain="neya iso hurekikoro cise ohta san"
	gloss="that bear die house LOC come.down.SG"
	free="That bear died. The flatfish-man came down to the house."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="58 (Tuita 3, l. 23)"
	dialect="East"
	note="Piłsudski's own note glosses hure-koro = ray ‘die’ in this tale." />

The tale resolves in marriage, with the reciprocal <Gl t="RECP" /> `u-` plus
the collective — a near-obligatory pairing on reciprocal verbs in this dialect:

<Example
	ain="kakan mahpoo-ho pon kapariw ohkayo tura u-sam-ahci"
	gloss="governor daughter-POSS small flatfish man together.with RECP-marry-COLL"
	free="Kakan's daughter married the small flatfish-man."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2020" page="59 (Tuita 3, l. 24)"
	dialect="East"
	note="Reciprocal u- + COLL is near-obligatory on reciprocal verbs; bare sam does not take COLL." />

## Text 2 — West-coast *carahaw*: "Esaman Carahaw" (The One-eyed Otter)

This west-coast Tarantomari "rumour tale" was recorded from Chiri's field notes
and re-edited by <Cite key="Sakaguchi 2019a" paren={false} />. It is told in the
third person throughout — the west-coast norm — with `an=` functioning as a
plain indefinite/passive rather than as a logophoric narrator. It opens with
the locative postposition <W w="otta" gloss="at, in" /> (&lt; *or-ta*) and the
existential closed by `manu`:

<Example
	ain="usoro otta tu-uruwan okkaw an manu"
	gloss="Usoro LOC two-sibling man exist.SG REP"
	free="In Usoro there were two brothers, it is said."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019a" page="137 (l. 2)"
	dialect="West"
	note="West/SW okkaw ‘man’ retains the coda stop (vs general Sakhalin ohkayo)." />

The monster is introduced with the west-coast intensifier `wen-poro` "extremely
big" (<Gl t="EMPH" /> `wen-` + `poro` "big"):

<Example
	ain="wen-poro hekay esaman"
	gloss="EMPH-big aged otter"
	free="a very big, aged otter"
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019a" page="139 (l. 17)"
	dialect="West"
	note="West-coast intensifier wen-poro ‘extremely big’; esaman ‘otter’." />

When the brothers shoot it, the connective <W w="neanpe" gloss="when, then" />
links the protasis to the result; the line closes, as folktale lines do, with
`manu`. Note that the west coast here retains the final vowel of `cotca`:

<Example
	ain="cotca neanpe ray manu"
	gloss="shoot.at CONJ die REP"
	free="When they shot it, it died, it is said."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019a" page="140 (l. 14)"
	dialect="West"
	note="Connective (ne)anpe ‘when’; sentence-final reportative manu." />

The protasis–consequence pattern is recurrent in this text. The connective
`neanpe` is preceded by a verb nominalised with `-hV` — here `oromos-u` "wake
up" with the belonging form `haw-he` "its voice" as the trigger:

<Example
	ain="hemata haw-he oromos-u neanpe"
	gloss="what voice-POSS wake.up-NMLZ CONJ"
	free="When he woke up at some strange voice,"
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019a" page="137 (l. 4)"
	dialect="West"
	note="Belonging form haw-he ‘its voice’; nominalised verb + neanpe ‘when’." />

The flight scene chains a causal `kusu` and the clause-linker <Gl t="CONJ" />
`ike`, and uses the SW quantifier `imiki` "all" (the general-Sakhalin form is
`emuyke`). The reduced west-coast ablative `ora` (&lt; *orowa*) marks the
agent of the following passive-like clause:

<Example
	ain="nean-pe kusu oman ike anih[i] nuso seta-h[a] imiki erapika"
	gloss="that-NMLZ because go.SG CONJ 3SG.PRO sled dog-POSS all unleash"
	free="Because of that, fleeing, he unleashed all the dogs from the sled."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019a" page="138 (l. 8)"
	dialect="West"
	note="Causal kusu; clause-linker ike; quantifier imiki ‘all’; overt pronoun anih for emphasis." />

<Example
	ain="seta ora kopiwke kimun ne kira"
	gloss="dog ABL 3SG.O.attack mountain.ALL ALL flee.SG"
	free="Chased by the dogs, the monster fled to the mountain."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019a" page="139 (l. 9)"
	dialect="West"
	note="West-coast reduced ablative ora (&lt; orowa) marking the agent; kim-un ‘to the mountain’, allative ne." />

The denouement uses the converb <Gl t="CONJ" /> `te` (the west-coast form of
`teh`) to link the descent and the telling, with the time-NP fronted and the
belonging form `sinkeke-he` "the next day":

<Example
	ain="sinkeke-h[e] anih[i] otaka ta san te eayrap"
	gloss="next.day-POSS 3SG.PRO beach LOC descend.SG CONJ recount"
	free="The next day, he went down to the beach and told the people about it."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019a" page="139 (l. 10)"
	dialect="West"
	note="Locative ta; converbal te (interval-linking ‘and then’); time-NP fronted." />

## Text 3 — West-coast *ubepekere*: "Karafuto Ubepekere" (the Panke/Penke neighbours)

This tale, recorded in katakana by Yamamoto Tasuke from Kimura Usarusmah of
Aihama and re-edited by <Cite key="Sakaguchi 2019b" paren={false} />, is the
Sakhalin instance of the pan-Ainu "neighbours" tale-type, with paired
protagonists <W w="panke" gloss="downstream man" /> and <W w="penke" gloss="upstream man" /> (the Sakhalin counterparts of the
Hokkaido Panampe/Penampe). Because the katakana source carries only a word-level
Japanese gloss, several segmentations here are conservative and a few lines
remain partly unanalysed; these are flagged.

The two neighbours are introduced with the converb `wa` plus the existential
`an`, and a chain of right-headed predicates preceding it:

<Example
	ain="penke aynu [kiyanne] aynu panke aynu poneyne usoyun wa an"
	gloss="upstream person elder person downstream person be.younger be.neighbours CONJ exist.SG"
	free="There were an upstream man, the elder, and a downstream man, the younger, living as neighbours."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019b" page="114 (l. 11801)"
	dialect="West"
	note="Converbal wa + an ‘be V-ing’; recorded at Aihama; segmentation partly Sakaguchi's, partly mine." />

A compound noun shows the SW coda pattern: `pon-cikah` "sparrow" (literally
"small bird"), where the coda would be `-p` further south:

<Example
	ain="sine haciko pon-cikah rayke"
	gloss="one small sparrow kill"
	free="He killed one little sparrow."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019b" page="115 (l. 11802)"
	dialect="West"
	note="pon-cikah ‘sparrow’ (lit. small-bird); West coda -h for the older -p; haciko ‘small’." />

A protasis with the magical-prayer verb `inonitah` resolves with the negative
existential `isan` (&lt; *isam*, with West final *m* &gt; *n*) and the quantifier
`emuyke` "all" — note that this same text uses both the general `emuyke` and the
SW `imiki`:

<Example
	ain="inonitah neya si emuyke isan"
	gloss="pray that feces all not.exist"
	free="When he prayed, all that feces disappeared."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019b" page="119 (l. 12002)"
	dialect="West"
	note="emuyke ‘all’ (general Sakhalin); isan ‘not exist’; segmentation mine, glosses from Sakaguchi's word glosses. [uncertain]" />

The reward scene gathers the restrictive <Gl t="RESTR" /> `pateh` "only", the
comitative <Gl t="COM" /> `tura` "together (with it)", and the collective on the
verb of giving:

<Example
	ain="sine ikoro sehpa ta pateh an=konte-si numano cise ohta tura oman"
	gloss="one treasure clasp FOC only 1.A=give-COLL gladly house LOC together go.SG"
	free="She was given only one treasure, a clasp, and gladly took it back home."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019b" page="117 (l. 11903)"
	dialect="West"
	note="Restrictive pateh ‘only’; locative ohta; comitative tura(no) ‘together’." />

The reversal — the greedy brother's house full of nothing but excrement — uses
the locative `ta`, the restrictive `pateh`, the sequential `neya` "then", and
closes with `manu`:

<Example
	ain="[Pankankuh] hoskiramu cise ta oman inkara neya [si] pateh an manu"
	gloss="Pankankuh elder.brother house LOC go.SG look.at then feces only exist.SG REP"
	free="Pankankuh went to the elder brother's house and looked, and there was only feces, it is said."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2019b" page="118 (l. 11910)"
	dialect="West"
	note="Locative ta; restrictive pateh; reportative manu; sequential neya ‘then’." />

## Text 4 — West-central dialogues: Dobrotvorskij (1875)

The two short Ainu texts appended to <Cite key="Dobrotvorskij 1875" paren={false} />'s
Ainu–Russian dictionary — a confession scene narrated by Ciwokanke and a
request/marriage dialogue — are the oldest connected Sakhalin Ainu prose, from
the West-central Kushunnai area, re-edited by <Cite key="Sakaguchi 2021" paren={false} />.
Their Cyrillic transcription faithfully records syllable-final consonants but
confuses *i*/*e* and *o*/*u* and ignores vowel length, so the fine morphology of
several forms is [uncertain]; the segmentations below follow Sakaguchi's notes.
What the texts most clearly attest is the **east-coast-style first-person
system** — the AN-class `-an`/`an=` and, diagnostically, the KU/CI-class object
prefix `in-` — confirming that this West-central material patterns with the East
rather than with the northern West coast.

The confession opens with a purposive `kusu` linking two AN-class verbs:

<Example
	ain="tan kotan ohta utasa-an kusu ariki-an"
	gloss="this village LOC visit-PRM.S in.order.to come.PL-PRM.S"
	surface="Tan kotàn ohtà utása-an kusú áriki-an."
	free="I have come in order to visit this village."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2021" page="49 (Dobrotvorskij text 1, ex. 1)"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="AN-class -an on both verbs; purposive kusu. Segmentation following Sakaguchi's romanisation." />

An AN-class transitive frame `an=e=…` "I … you" expresses gratitude for the
visit, with `renkayne` "thanks to, because":

<Example
	ain="tan kotan ta eh renkayne an=e=nukara"
	gloss="this village LOC come thanks.to 1.A=2.O=see"
	surface="Tan kotán ta eh renkáyne, an-è-núkara."
	free="Thanks to your coming to this village, I have been able to see you."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2021" page="49 (Dobrotvorskij text 1, ex. 3)"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="AN-class transitive 1A=2O frame an=e=…; renkayne ‘thanks to’." />

The diagnostic line uses the KU/CI-class 1SG object prefix `in-` inside an
otherwise AN-class context, together with the causative <Gl t="CAUS" /> `-re`
and reflexive `yay-`:

<Example
	ain="tama in=konte reekoro yay-irayki-re-an"
	gloss="jewel 1SG.O=give very REFL-thank-CAUS-PRM.S"
	surface="Tamà in-konte. Rékoro yay'iráykire-an."
	free="You gave me a jewel. I am very grateful."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2021" page="49 (Dobrotvorskij text 1, ex. 5)"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="KU/CI-class 1SG object prefix in- in an AN-class context — diagnostic of the in-/i- split." />

A conditional with `ciki` "if" and the adverbialiser <Gl t="ADV" /> `-no`
closes the parting advice:

<Example
	ain="pirika-no oman ciki pirika"
	gloss="good-ADV go.SG if good"
	surface="Pírikano omán ciki pírika."
	free="It would be good if you went carefully."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2021" page="49 (Dobrotvorskij text 1, ex. 6)"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="Adverbialiser -no; conditional ciki ‘if’." />

The second text contrasts the AN-class object prefix `i-` (with the free pronoun
`anokay`) against the `in-` of the first text, and negates with `hanne`:

<Example
	ain="anokay an=renkayne i=koyki anpe ka hanne"
	gloss="1SG.PRO 1.S=accordingly 1.O=hit NMLZ even NEG"
	surface="Anokay an-renkayne, i-koyki ánpe ka hánne."
	free="In accordance with my wish, I was not hit."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2021" page="50 (Dobrotvorskij text 2, ex. 8)"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="AN-class object prefix i- (with pronoun anokay); negative hanne. The dictionary also records the parallel kuani … in-koyki, showing the KU/AN object contrast." />

A concessive `yahka` "even if" and the epistemic `nankoro pe ne` "it would
probably be" round out the dialogue's politeness formulae:

<Example
	ain="sine utah-ta ne kusu porono ham e=(i=)ye yahka pirika nankoro pe ne"
	gloss="one relative-? COP because much NEG 2.A=(1.O=)say even good probably NMLZ COP"
	free="Because we are close kin, it would be fine even if you did not say much to me."
	cite="Sakaguchi 2021" page="52 (Dobrotvorskij text 2, ex. 21)"
	dialect="Sakhalin"
	note="Concessive yahka ‘even if’; nankoro pe ne ‘it probably is’; utahta flagged ‘meaning unknown’ by Sakaguchi. [uncertain]" />

## Text 5 — Modern Enchiw and native-written texts

The final group illustrates the <strong>living tail</strong> of the documentary record:
modern west-coast revival prose, and an east-coast text written by a native
speaker rather than dictated to a researcher. They show that the same
constructions — `manu`, `an=`, the belonging form, the additive `naa` — persist
into didactic and self-authored registers.

In a modern west-coast didactic dialogue, `an=` functions as a plain
indefinite/passive ("she was raised"), and the line closes with the hearsay
`manu`:

<Example
	ain="aaca haciko ohta siisam hatagoya ohta an=reske manu"
	gloss="father small LOC Japanese inn LOC PRM.A=raise REP"
	free="Father: She was raised in a Japanese inn when she was little, it is said."
	cite="Kitahara 2016"
	dialect="West"
	note="an= as indefinite-person/passive; hearsay manu; modern pan-West didactic register." />

The KU-class possessive prefix `ku=` on the belonging form `ahci-hi` "(my)
grandmother", with two additive `naa` "too":

<Example
	ain="aaca ku=ahci-hi kawren itah naa nuca itah naa ponno wante manu"
	gloss="father 1SG=grandmother-POSS Korean language too Russian language too a.little know REP"
	free="Father: My grandmother understood a little Korean and Russian too, it is said."
	cite="Kitahara 2016"
	dialect="West"
	note="KU-class possessive prefix ku=; additive naa ‘too’; hearsay manu." />

A west-coast oral-history excerpt from the Tarantomari narrator Yamada Hayo
chains the reflexive `yay-` and the AN-class first person (here a 1PL) on the
plural existential `okay`:

<Example
	ain="yay-sukukka te okay-an manu"
	gloss="REFL-support.oneself CONJ live.PL-PRM.S REP"
	surface="yáysukukka te oká am manu"
	free="We lived supporting ourselves, it is said."
	cite="Yamada (ELPR)"
	dialect="West"
	note="Reflexive yay-; AN-class first person (1PL inclusive) on PL existential okay; ELPR transcription." />

The same narrator's first-person discovery uses the AN-class S on `inkar`
"look" and the intensifier `wen-poro` "very big" seen in the Esaman tale above:

<Example
	ain="inkar-an manu reekor wen-poro-kotan"
	gloss="look-PRM.S REP very EMPH-big-village"
	surface="ínkarán manu, ré:kor wémporokotan"
	free="I looked, and saw a very large village, it is said."
	cite="Yamada (ELPR)"
	dialect="West"
	note="wen-poro ‘very big’ (lit. EMPH-big), the same West-coast intensifier as in Text 2; AN-class S on inkar." />

Finally, an east-coast text self-written by Sentoku Tarōji of Naibuchi in a
letter to Piłsudski (c. 1900s) — a rare native-authored document — uses
`maci koro` "take a wife" and the hearsay `manuy`:

<Example
	ain="tata maci koro manuy"
	gloss="there wife have REP"
	free="There he took a wife again, it is said."
	cite="Sentoku (letters)"
	dialect="East"
	note="maci koro ‘take a wife’; hearsay manuy. Self-written Ainu by an east-coast speaker." />

A folktale's conventional close pairs the reportative `manu` with the lexical
tale-closing formula <W w="hemaka" gloss="the end" />:

<Example
	ain="usoy ta pirika okay utara kii manu hemaka"
	gloss="neighbour LOC be.good exist.PL people 3PL.A.do REP end"
	free="Living as neighbours, the people lived well, it is said. The end."
	cite="Piłsudski 1912"
	dialect="East"
	note="Locative ta; reportative manu; conventional tale-closing hemaka." />

## What the texts show together

Read side by side, the five texts sort along a clear east–west line. The
<strong>east-coast</strong> *tuytah* (Text 1) and the West-central dialogues (Text 4) attest
the full first-person apparatus — the AN-class `-an`/`an=`, the KU/CI-class
object prefix `in-`, and the narrator-shifting use of the <Gl t="PRM" /> set —
while the <strong>west-coast</strong> tales (Texts 2–3) are consistently third-person
narratives in which `an=` has drifted toward a plain indefinite/passive, as <Cite key="Chiri 1942" paren={false} /> already observed.
The collective <Gl t="COLL" /> `-ahci`/`-hsi`/`-si` is everywhere on plural and
reciprocal predicates, and in Text 1 it does double duty as a passive marker —
though whether it is genuinely a passive or an impersonal plural yielding a
passive reading remains, as Sakaguchi cautions, an open question.

Phonologically the texts display the <strong>coda shibboleth</strong>: the west-coast SW
forms keep the older stops (`okkaw` "man", `pon-cikah` &lt; *-cikap*, `pateh`),
while the rest of Sakhalin debuccalises them to `-h` (`ohkayo`, `pateh` ~
`pate`). The lexical isoglosses surface too — SW `imiki` against general
`emuyke` "all", both within a single west-coast text. And across registers the
folktale grammar is invariant where Hokkaido would differ: the line-final
reportative `manu(u)` does not change form between hearsay and
traditional-knowledge readings, the quotative is `nah` (not Hokkaido *sekor*),
and the tale closes with `hemaka`. These are the connected-text correlates of
the features the body of the grammar has described one by one.
